T1  - International R &amp; D Rivalry and Industrial Strategy
PY  - 1983
Y1  - 1983/10/01
DO  - 10.2307/2297771
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 50
IS  - 4
SP  - 707
EP  - 722
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - This paper presents a theory of government intervention which provides an explanation for “industrial strategy” policies such as R &amp; D or export subsidies in imperfectly competitive international markets. Domestic net welfare is improved by the capture of a greater share of the output of rent earning industries, although the subsidy-ridden noncooperative international equilibrium is jointly suboptimal. Behaviour of governments and firms is modelled as a three stage subgame perfect Nash equilibrium. The assumption that the government is the first player in this game allows it to influence equilibrium outcomes by altering the set of credible actions open to firms.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2297771
ER  - 



